Vladimir Putin and the risks of a third world war.
San Francisco - February 24, The Russian invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of the 3rd World War that could potentially destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping had held a long meeting on February 4 - it was the day China celebrated the Lunar New Year and the Beijing Winter Olympics opened.
After the meeting, the two parties issued a carefully drafted document of over 5,000 words declaring the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is stronger than any treaty, and definitely needs to be negotiated in detail in advance.
I was shocked that Xi seemed to have entrusted Putin with invading and launching a war in Ukraine.
He believes that his confirmation as China's lifetime ruler later this year is just a formality, and he is confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After receiving Putin's support, he set out to achieve his lifelong dream in a way that was virtually unimaginable.
At nearly 70, Putin seems to think that if he wants to leave a lasting mark in Russian history, it's now or never.
However, his view on the impact of Russia in the world is distorted.
He seems to think that the Russian people need an emperor they can blindly follow.
This system is a stark opposite of democratic society, and this vision has warped the "soul" of the overly emotional and sentimental Russian people.
In my childhood, I often came into contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I launched what I call my political charity career.
Initially, I established a foundation in my native Hungary, and later, I actively participated in activities that contributed to the collapse of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this disintegration had already begun.
I have also established a foundation in Russia, and later in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to set up a foundation (I closed the foundation in 1989, before the Tiananmen Square Massacre broke out).
I personally don't know Putin, but I have closely followed his rise to power and thoroughly understand his cold-blooded character.
He reduced Chechnya's capital Grozny to rubble, and now he is threatening to do the same to Ukraine's capital, Kyiv.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB operative, but he seems to have changed recently.
He seemed to have lost touch with reality, as he had formed a fixed notion.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He thought Ukrainians who spoke Russian would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but in reality, they were no different from the rest of the Ukrainian-speaking population.
In the face of seemingly one-sided possibilities, the Ukrainian people still carried out an unbelievable heroic resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy article, stating that Russians and Ukrainians are, in fact, one nation, and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Because Kiev was the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, his argument was not entirely without historical basis.
But it was Putin who was misled in the second part.
He should have known more clearly about the fact.
Many Ukrainians bravely fought in the Euromaidan protests that broke out in 2014.
The event in 2014 made him very angry.
But when ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers, the Russian troops performed poorly.
The simultaneous granting of defense contracts also played an important role in perpetuating endemic corruption.
But Putin not only did not blame himself, but seemed to have gone mad instead.
He has made up his mind to punish Ukraine for its defiance, and his actions appear to be without constraint.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle and disregarded all rules of engagement, especially bombing civilian populations indiscriminately.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid that supplies the Chornobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also destroyed.
In the besieged Mariupol, up to 400,000 people have been without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia may very well lose this war.
Both the U.S. and the EU are sending defensive arms to Ukraine, and are also trying to purchase Russian MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These might change the entire situation.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already created a miracle in strengthening Europe's resolve and unity.
At the same time, Xi seems to have realized that Putin had strayed.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi reiterated that the friendship between China and Russia is "as solid as a rock," Xi sent a message to French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping activities.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to keep the utmost restraint in the war.
It is impossible to determine whether Putin will comply with Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be overthrown before they destroy our civilization.
